title: Ten: Foxtel deal won’t affect shows
text:
Email a friend 
CHANNEL 10 has assured TV viewers that the Competition watchdog’s (ACCC) approval of Foxtel’s purchase of up to 15 per cent of the network won’t have any impact on their favourite programs. 
Instead, the $77 million deal will allow Ten to pay down debt and provide the funds to continue building on the success it has achieved with in 2015. 
Ten has had a strong year with the launch of new shows including I’m A Celebrity … Get Me Out of Here, Gogglebox, The Shark Tank, The Great Australian Spelling Bee and The Bachelorette. Fan favourite ... Chris Brown and Julia Morris are back in 2016 with I'm A Celebrity ... Get Me Out Of Here! Picture: Supplied. Source: Channel 10 
Those programs have added to an arsenal that also includes Big Bash cricket, MasterChef Australia , Family Feud , and The Bachelor . Have You Been Paying Attention has also gained traction after a soft start. 
Ten has finally achieved some year-round ratings consistency and says the deal with Foxtel will help keep up the pressure on rivals Seven and Nine. Hit show ... The Bachelorette, with Sam Frost, has been a big winner for Ten. Picture: Supplied. Source: Supplied 
“There will be no change to what viewers see on their TV screens (on Ten, Eleven and ONE),” a Ten spokesman says. 
“What this does is gives us the funds to keep investing in prime time programming and continue the strategy of the past couple of years. 
“A number of our new shows have launched well. We’ve had good momentum. This deal will allow that to continue.” 
Ten is set to announce its 2016 program line-up, including some new programs, at its annual up-fronts event on November 19. Ten recently announced that I’m A Celebrity ... Get Me Out of Here! will definitely return next year. Ten is also expected to screen its Peter Brock miniseries, with Matthew Le Nevez in the driver’s seat, next year. 
Foxtel and Ten already jointly fund Gogglebox which has just commenced its second season on air.
